The map returned by `getComponentRegressionMap` should be something like:
```
{
    "component1": {
        "component2": 0.2,
        "component3": 0.1,
        ...
    },
    "component2": {
        "component4": 0.5,
        ...
    },
    ...
}
```

From this map, you should be able to build a heatmap composed of multiple rows and columns. The keys of the map ("component1" and "component2" above) will be the rows, the keys of the submaps ("component2", "component3", "component4" above) will be the columns. The color will be defined by the values in the submap (for the row-column "component1"-"component2" the color will be defined by map["component1"]["component2"], it would be 0.2 above).

@jrbenny35 you could add a generic function to draw the heatmap in common.js, with the characteristic I mentioned earlier:
>  The function should accept a list of source and target teams/components to filter the teams/components to draw in the heatmap (so, for example, in the team level view we will only show dependencies where the target of the dependency is the selected team).

In the graph.html page (you could start from there as a first usage of the function), you could draw the heatmap for a specific component/team (you can hardcode it at first).
